My family will not be getting the vaccine in the near future. I question it's short term and long term effects on our health. I also question how effective it really is. My mother got the vaccine and the optional booster then contracted covid and was very sick. Same case for at least 6+ other people I know. From my understanding, the vaccine doesn't effect the rate of transmission, so I think that the only reason mandates are in place is to lessen the amount of money the local and federal governments have to spend on managing covid cases, as well as reducing the over flooding of hospitals. I also question the long term effectiveness as covid strains mutate. There is every chance that the next mutation will not be effected by the current vaccine which would create a new wave of new vaccine mandates and protocols. The cycle could continue, creating the same system we see in flu shots. They offer a vaccine protecting against a different variation every year, which is rarely ever effective. Then people are constantly flooding their bodies with tons of ingredients that can be harmful in the short and long term. In addition to those concerns, I also worry that since the covid vaccine doesn't effect transmission but reduces the likelihood of experiencing symptoms, it's creating an army of asymptomatic carriers. We're seeing the same type of spikes in infection rates as we were when elementary schools were reopened. In that case, since children are much more likely to be infected without showing symptoms, elementary students would often be asymptomatic carriers and attend school as usual. They would pass it to their fellow students who would pass it to their parents, then their parents would unknowingly expose people to the virus before their own symptoms started. I think the vaccine game is a dangerous one, and this vaccine is going the same route as the aids vaccine. The only question to me is "How much chaos and damage will it do before it's finally stopped?".

The original endpoint of the study was the insultingly low goal of reducing hospital admissions, and due to multiple problems with study design (failing to test symptomatic participants in the vaccine group, failure to double blind, etc) I do not believe the manufacturers' effectiveness claims are reliable. This coupled with a concerning number of reported injuries and deaths makes the decision easy.  I will not get the vaccine and neither will my children. At best it reduces symptoms, and my family has already had Covid with extremely mild symptoms that we recovered easily from. This entire virus has been ridiculously overblown and politicized. Any viewpoints not aligning with the official narrative (even those from medical professionals, virologists, pharmaceutical experts, and others qualified to speak) have been suppressed.  Hysterical cries about the number of deaths overlook similar or greater rates of death from preventable causes such as heart disease. Until we get hysterical about obesity, I don't see a reason to become hysterical over a virus that is now endemic.

I am also very annoyed that this country refuses to acknowledge any nuance. Many/most other first world countries consider someone who had COVID and one shot of a 2 shot series to be fully vaccinated. A person who had COVID and one shot was shown to produce more antibodies than someone who?d never had COVID and got both shots. Because I had symptomatic, diagnosed COVID, I chose to only get one shot.
